question.lead:
Welcome to this survey!

This survey is part of my (Kevin Gomez Buquerin) PhD research. It covers the subject area of automotive digital forensics. The contracting authority is myself. The Technical University Ingolstadt (https://www.thi.de) is the supporting research institution.

Requirements stated by the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) are fulfilled. No personal data is collected. SoSci Survey provides further information under the following URL: https://www.soscisurvey.de/en/privacy



What can I expect here?

The following survey consists of three sections. Each section contains different questions related to digital forensics and automotive systems. Automotive systems include in-vehicle components (e.g. ECUs) and components directly connected to vehicles (e.g. OEM backends, smartphones, OBD dongles)

First, questions about general experience and known data formats in digital forensics are in scope. Next, questions regarding digital forensic tools in the area of in-vehicle as well as automotive related systems are of interest. The last section contains questions about 11 automotive components and related data formats.


What is the benefit of this survey?

My goal is to evaluate coverage, experience, and knowledge of tools and data formats used in automotive digital forensics. Further, this survey aims to identify additional tools and data formats known by experts.

Based on the results of this survey, we identify relevant data formats. This helps researchers to create extraction and analysis methods for automotive digital forensic investigations.



Do I have to answer everything?

No, you don't! I want to state that the participation is voluntary and not mandatory. Feel free to skip questions.

question.title: Experience
question.explanation: How would you describe your experience in the following areas?

question.title: Data formats
question.explanation: There are different known data formats in digital forensics and automotive. Which of the following data formats do you know?

item.text: Memory dumps created by using debugging interfaces, such as JTAG, on the hardware component
PDF files from Event Data Recorder products

question.lead:
Tools

The following questions relate to digital forensic for automotive systems only.

question.title: Tools for automotive digital forensics
question.explanation: There are different known tools for digital forensics for automotive and related systems (such as smartphones or Car-to-X). Which of the following tools do you know?

question.title: Do you know additional tools related to automotive digital forensics?

question.lead:
Data Formats for Automotive Components

Data formats vary between components. Further, extracted data formats depend on the used tool. Those tools distinguish between automotive components.

The following questions are specific for 11 different automotive components. Each question aims to identify additional known data formats for the specific component.

Known data formats (prior section) are:

  • Memory dumps created by using debugging interfaces, such as JTAG, on the hardware component
  • eMMC memory dumps
  • JSON files
  • USB image
  • SD-card image
  • Hardware Security Module (HSM) data
  • Trusted Platform Module (TPM) data
  • PDF files from Event Data Recorder products
  • CDR files from Bosch Crash Data Retrieval products
  • JSON files from Tesla Event Data Retrieval products
  • Berla iVe exports
  • Cellebrite exports
  • Oxygen Forensics exports
  • Magnet Axiom exports
  • E01 files
  • CSV files
  • XLS files
  • XRY from MSAB
  • GPX files
  • KML files
  • Software Defined Radio (SDR) captures
  • Packet Captures (PCAP)
  • UDX files
  • DBC files



Which other data formats do you know or could you imagine for the following automotive components?

question.title: Battery related systems
question.explanation: Battery related systems include in-vehicle battery management systems and external charging stations.

question.title: End-point devices
question.explanation: End-point devices include mobile devices, backend systems, and OBD dongles. Such devices can be connected to the vehicle in several ways (e.g. via Internet connection, direct connection, etc.).

question.title: Telematics control units
question.explanation: Telematic control units include Car2X components and other communication related components (e.g. to manufacturer backend).

question.title: Infotainment systems
question.explanation: Infotainment systems include Audi MMI, BMW iDrive, or Mercedes-Benz MBUX. These systems are not classified as end-point devices. However, infotainment systems allow connections and communication with end-point devices.

question.title: External navigation systems
question.explanation: External Navigation Systems include mobile GPS systems from Garmin or TomTom.

question.title: Comfort systems
question.explanation: Comfort systems control stored seat positions, air conditioning preferences, and in-vehicle temperature settings.

question.title: Immobilizer systems
question.explanation: Immobilizer systems includes key fobs and in-vehicle receivers and cryptographic components.

question.title: Gateways
question.explanation: Gateways translate information between different bus protocols and filter information.

question.title: Safety monitoring systems
question.explanation: Safety monitoring systems monitor vehicle surroundings and passengers. Examples are NXPs Driver/Occupant Monitoring systems.

question.title: eCall components
question.explanation: This includes embedded components (mandatory since April 2018) and external devices such as Bosch “Unfallstecker”. These devices automatically make a emergency call. eCall systems are not the same as Airbag components.

question.title: Airbag systems
question.explanation: Airbag systems are installed within the vehicle and collect different predefined information such as vehicle speed, accelerator of the pedal, service brake activation, and more.
Do you know additional in-vehicle or vehicle-connected components?

question.lead: Other components not mentioned in the prior questions

Thank you for completing this questionnaire and participating at this research!

I would like to thank you very much for helping.

Feel free to contact me, if you have further questions or subjects you want to discuss. You are able to contact me under the following e-mail address: extern.KevinKlaus.GomezBuquerin@thi.de
